%% Pattern Documentation
%% ==================
%% Pattern Name: Hierarchical Pattern
%% Article: Article 2 - Multi-Agent Coordination Patterns
%%
%% Pattern Description:
%% The Hierarchical Pattern organizes agents in a multi-level management structure,
%% mirroring organizational hierarchies. Strategic decisions flow down while operational
%% data flows up, creating layers of abstraction that manage complexity at scale.
%% Each level has authority over its subordinates and responsibility to its superiors.
%%
%% Business Value:
%% - Scalability: Manage complexity through layering
%% - Clarity: Mirrors organizational structure (intuitive for humans)
%% - Autonomy: Each level makes decisions within its scope
%% - Information Flow: Strategic down, operational up
%% - Accountability: Clear responsibility at each level
%%
%% Key Characteristics:
%% 1. Multiple Levels: CEO ‚Üí Managers ‚Üí Supervisors ‚Üí Workers
%% 2. Chain of Command: Clear reporting structure
%% 3. Delegation: Each level delegates to subordinates
%% 4. Aggregation: Each level aggregates subordinate results
%% 5. Strategy Cascade: Top-level goals flow down with translations
%%
%% Real-World Use Cases:
%% 1. Global Supply Chain Coordination
%%    - Strategic: Demand forecasting, capacity planning
%%    - Regional: Inventory optimization per geography (4 regions)
%%    - Operational: Order fulfillment, shipping (20+ agents)
%%    - Result: 8‚Üí12 inventory turns, -67% stockouts, $45M WC reduction, 87%‚Üí96% on-time
%%
%% 2. Large Enterprise IT Operations
%%    - Strategic: Infrastructure planning, budget allocation
%%    - Regional: Data center operations, backup procedures
%%    - Team: Server management, database administration
%%    - Result: 99.99% uptime, faster incident response
%%
%% 3. Global Pharmaceutical R&D
%%    - Strategic: Portfolio planning, molecule prioritization
%%    - Regional: Trial site coordination, regulatory compliance
%%    - Operational: Lab experiments, data collection
%%    - Result: Faster time-to-market, better regulatory alignment
%%
%% 4. Financial Services Risk Management
%%    - Strategic: Risk appetite, capital allocation
%%    - Division: Credit risk, market risk, operational risk
%%    - Desk: Individual position management
%%    - Result: Better risk visibility, regulatory compliance
%%
%% 5. Marketing Campaign Management
%%    - Strategic: Brand positioning, budget allocation
%%    - Regional: Market adaptation, local campaigns
%%    - Operational: Content creation, execution
%%    - Result: Consistent branding with local relevance
%%
%% 6. Project Portfolio Management
%%    - Strategic: Portfolio-level optimization
%%    - Program: Cross-project coordination
%%    - Project: Individual project execution
%%    - Result: Better resource allocation, higher success rate
%%
%% Implementation Patterns:
%% - Top-Down Planning: Strategic decisions flow down
%% - Bottom-Up Reporting: Operational metrics flow up
%% - Delegation: Each level delegates to next
%% - Goal Cascade: Translate strategic goals to tactical
%% - Exception Management: Escalate unexpected situations
%%
%% When To Use:
%% ‚úì Large-scale systems requiring multiple management levels
%% ‚úì Organization mirrors agent structure (natural fit)
%% ‚úì Need to manage complexity through layering
%% ‚úì Different decision types at different levels
%% ‚úì Clear accountability structures required
%%
%% When NOT To Use:
%% ‚úó Small systems (overhead not justified)
%% ‚úó Highly interdependent tasks (hierarchies create delays)
%% ‚úó Need for rapid decision-making
%%
%% Organizational Levels:
%% 1. Strategic (Top): Long-term planning, budgets, priorities
%% 2. Tactical (Middle): Translate strategy to operations, coordinate
%% 3. Operational (Bottom): Execute tasks, collect metrics
%%
%% Information Flow:
%% - DOWN: Goals, budgets, priorities, strategies
%% - UP: Metrics, exceptions, status, performance
%% - ACROSS: Coordination between peers
%%
%% Performance Characteristics:
%% - Latency: Communication overhead increases with levels
%% - Throughput: Scales with number of workers
%% - Scalability: Excellent (designed for scale)
%% - Resilience: High (distributed authority)
%% - Cost: Proportional to number of agents
%%
%% Failure Handling:
%% - Local Failures: Managed at lowest appropriate level
%% - Escalation: Unresolved issues escalate to superiors
%% - Redundancy: Peer coverage if agent fails
%% - Rebalancing: Redistribute work if level fails
%%
%% Related Patterns:
%% - Supervisor Pattern: Single-level routing
%% - Handoff Pattern: Transfer between specialists
%% - Parallel Pattern: Sibling agents working together
%% - Network/Swarm: Flat peer-to-peer vs hierarchical
